Notes for JOSEPH SNIDER HUNTSMAN:

I, Joseph Huntsman,of the county of Belmont and State of Ohio, do make and publish this my last will and testament in manner and form following, that is to say:

 

First, it is my will that my funeral expenses and all my just debts be fully paid.

Second, I give and bequeath to my beloved wife, Martha Huntsman the one third of the remainder of my property.

Third, after the above is deducted, I give of the remainder Thirty dollars to my son Joseph (exclusive of his equal share, if he stays with me during my illness)

Fourth, It is my request that the remainder of my property be divided into six equal portions, and distributed among my children, each a portion.

Fifth, the girl shall have her portion paid her as soon as she arrives at the age of sixteen, or at her marriage should she be married before that age, and the boys shall have theirs at the age of seventeen.

Sixth, I wish it understood that the property shall be sold and then the above dividends made.

And Lastly, I hereby constitute and appoint my said wife Martha Huntsman and Henry Thurston to be executors for this my last will and testament, revoking and annulling all former wills by me made and satifying and confiming this and no other to be my last will and testament.

 

In testimony whereof, I have hereunto set my hand and seal this 30th day of March 1836.

 

Signed and Pulished in presence of us

John Alleyer

Henry Thurston Joseph X Huntsman

(his mark)

Notes for WILLIAM HUNTSMAN:

William Huntsman, a young man aged 32 years, was struck by a passenger train on the Wheeling & Lake road on last Saturday evening a mile west of Unionvale, and was killed instantly.

He had made his home with his brother, Mr. James M. Huntsman of Green Township, for the past three years. On Saturday evening about five o'clock he had dressed himself and started on foot along the railroad track, intending to visit some friends in the neighborhood of Unionvale. No one saw the accident, but the engineer of the east-bound passenger train thought his engine had struck someone, though in the darkness he was not quite certain. On reaching Unionvale he gave information to this effect, and Mr. Kerr, the station agent accompanied by Mr. James Shepler and Mr. Singer, took lanterns and went along the track and found the body at the place described.

A coroner's inquest was held by Mr. D.P. Host, who had been deputized to act, but the testimony elicited only that facts stated above, the case being a pure accident, with no one to blame.

Mr. Huntsman was a young man who was held in high esteem by all who knew him, and was loved by every member of his brother's family as one of their own. His funeral was held at Bridgeport, at the home of his mother, on Wednesday, this week.

Notes for SAMUEL GLASGOW:

Moved to St. Marys, Kansas in 1876

 

St. Marys Star, November 10, 1905:

 

AN OLD SETTLER GONE

On Thursday, November 2nd, shortly before midnight, Samuel Glasgow died at his home of heart disease at the age of 69 years after a lingering illness. He was born in Belmont County, Ohio, October 31, 1836 and was married to Miss Nancy M. Huntsman in the county of his birth on August 6, 1856. Fourteen children, 11 girls and 3 boys, were born to their union, all of whom survive the parents with the except of 4 girls. The deceased enlisted in the United States Service at Columbus, Ohio, June 4, 1861, and was honorably discharged there from June 26, 1864.

With his family, he came to Kansas in March 1876 locating in St. Marys. He resided in the city for nine years when he moved just west of town and built a small home in which he lived for several years. In the meantime, a number of people erected homes near his and the little hamlet was give the name of Glasgowtown a few years ago in honor of the subject of this sketch. Mr. Glasgow later sold his first home and built a large one not far from it where he passed away.

The funeral services were conducted by Rev. B.F. Parlette of the Methodist Church at the home of the deceased Saturday afternoon and the remains were laid beside those of his wife in the Protestant Cemetery.

Samuel Glasgow was hone and well thought of..he loved free thought and free speech; he shouldered a gun away back in the sixties and fought for his country when it need the assistance of its citizens. His memory deserves the universal respect of those for whom he fought.

Mrs. Huntsman, wife of Mr. J.M.Huntsman of Green Township this county, died on Tuesday, August 15, 1911, aged nearly 58 years. She was born near Cadiz in October, 1853, and was a daughter of the late J.W. Davis of Cadiz. She was a loving and devoted wife and mother, the light of the home circle, and dearer than all the world beside to husband and children. She was laid to rest in the Cadiz cemetery, the funeral services being conducted by her pastor, Dr. Henthorne, assisted by Rev. Dr. S.H. Doyle of Philadelphia, a cousin of Mr. Huntsman.

Notes for JOHN W. HUNTSMAN:

August 26, 1915 Newspaper Clipping:

 

J.W.Huntsman, aged about 52 years, a miner living at Nevada, a small village, five miles west of this place, committed suicide at his home about noon Sunday. In committing the deed he used a shotgun, attaching a shoestring to the trigger, the discharge taking effect in the left breast, causing instant death.

Ill health, coupled with the fact that he was recently robbed of a sum of money, are assigned as causes for the rash act. The deceased is survived by his wife and six children. The funeral occurred Tuesday, conducted by Rev. L.S. Rose.

The Times Recorder - Zanesville, Ohio

Tuesday, 2 December 1924, page 2

Headline: Son Committed Suicide

 

Mrs. W. M. Huntsman of Brown's Heights was called to Cadiz (OH) Sunday by

the death of her son, Grover Huntsman, age 34, who committed suicide by

hanging himself Saturday near his home. Mr. Huntsman resided in Cambridge

until a few years ago when he came to Cadiz to reside. He was apparently in

good spirits and no motive for his desire to end his life. Mr. Huntsman is

survived by his widow and two children, Francis and Harry Huntsman, in

addition to his parents and brothers residing in Cambridge. Funeral

services will be held at the home in Cadiz Tuesday at noon.

Notes for DAVID MCCLELLAND HUNTSMAN:

D.M. Huntsman, prominent citizen of Somerset Township and widely known throughout the county, passed away at his home Tuesday morning due to a cerebral hemorrhage Monday night from which he never rallied.

David McClelland Huntsman was born near Atlas March 20, 1866, and has lived in that community the greater part of his life with the exception of a few years in Barnesville, moving to Somerton in 1927.

He was a farmer and for several years was a commissioner of Belmont County, highly respected and capable in county affairs. His wife preceded him in death twelve years ago, but he is survived by five sons: Forest and Lowell Huntsman, Newcomerstown; Lawrence Huntsman, Barnesville; Paul Huntsman, in the home. He leaves one sister, Miss Mary Huntsman, Baileys Mills; one daughter is deceased.

Funeral service will be held this Thursday afternoon in the Somerton Church of Christ conducted by Evangelist James Gallagher. Burial will be made at Boston.

 

(Newspaper clipping dated January 1909)

 

Four of Family Ill

 

A letter received by the News Wednesday from D.M. Huntsman county commissior elect of Somerset Township, states that he is yet confined to his home from the effects of his severe attack of typhoid fever. Mr. Huntsman has not been farther from his housse than the barn since the 30th day of October and while the worst is over in his case he is not yet himself by an means. In addition to his own illness, his wife and two sons have been very ill with the same malady. His youngest son has been in bed 9 days and is still in a serious condition while the older son has just recovered. Mrs. Huntsman has been confined to her bed for 36 days but is now in a fair way to recover.

Mr. Huntsman and family have been having more than their share of sickness, four members of the family of six being ill with the fever at the same time. The many friends of Commisioner-elect Huntsman will regret to learn of his complicated troubles, but will be glad when they are all well again.

OHIO VALLEY NEWS...
